name: Mary Peltola
tweet_text: I was the only candidate in the forum that supported our rigorous environmental standards while my fellow Democrat called for loosening of these regulations.

name: Mary Peltola
tweet_text: I support the Ambler road on the conditions that it remains private to protect the subsistence needs of local residents, meets rigorous environmental standards, prioritizes local hires, and is supported by the majority of those who the development would directly impact.

name: Mary Peltola
tweet_text: Re:ANWR‚Äîmy support of possible exploration is exclusively confined to the 1002 Area, a small sliver of the larger reserve. Alaskans have consistently supported exploration in this area. Studies show minimal impact on local subsistence species & huge benefits to our local economy.

name: Mary Peltola
tweet_text: Yet resource development can bring good jobs and much-needed infrastructure to areas with struggling economies, and this must be weighed against potential environmental impacts.

name: Mary Peltola
tweet_text: I believe in responsible resource development only when projects have a social license to operate from the local community and appropriate environmental protections. This is why, for example, I don‚Äôt support Pebble.

name: Mary Peltola
tweet_text: Responsible natural resource usage has been and will continue to be a pillar of our livelihood.

name: Mary Peltola
tweet_text: My priority has always been to do what‚Äôs best for Alaska. That means both protecting the rivers, mountains, and tundra we call home, as well as providing a viable economic future for the people who live in every part of the state, rural and urban alike.

name: Mary Peltola
tweet_text:
As a Native woman born and raised in rural Alaska and the only rural candidate in this race I have a nuanced perspective on responsible resource development and believe that it needs to be taken one project at a time.
